Have you Heard?
Numerous clean, airy galleries highlight and display ancient to modern American Indian artifacts and art in tastefully designed, well-lit spaces.
This private, nonprofit museum has earned an international reputation for its thorough and sensitive portrayal and presentation of Native cultures, heritage and lifestyle, in particular, those in the Southwest.
The Hopi Katsina doll collection must be one of the largest and most complete in the nation.
These dolls, or "visible prayers", are as beautiful to see as they are complex in description.
The 1910-1945 Goldwater-Kibbey Collection is a must-see for its historical importance and cultural representation.
For more information, as well as collecting tips, visit: www.heard.org/katsinadolls  In addition to providing residents and visitors an unparalleled source of Southwest American Indian cultural information, this museum offers a learning center, shops specializing in Native gifts and books, student art shows, a library and archives, a pleasingly cool courtyard, two gardens and a very decent café where I had one of the tastiest chicken quesedillas I've found anywhere.
P.S., there is no need to correct my use of the term Katsina over "Kachina".
Though they're the same thing, the pronunciation of "Katsina" more nearly approximates the Hopi language.
So who says I'm culturally inept, ignorant or insensitive?
Now you've heard...and the word is Heard.

